heading.content: Lessons in Chemistry By Bonnie Garmus

sentences.content: In 1961, women wore long-sleeved dresses, joined garden clubs, and raised kids.
Nobody knew there would be a '60s movement.
After the big wars, people felt fresh and believed everything was possible.
That was not the case for Elizabeth Zott, a 30-year-old mother.
Elizabeth woke up every morning and was sure of one thing: her life was over.
Elizabeth went to the kitchen to make her daughter Madeline lunch.
On a note, she wrote, Fuel for learning.
She paused, Play sports at recess, but do not automatically let the boys win.
She paused again and wrote, It is not your imagination.
Most people are awful.
Madeline was a gifted child.
She learned to read at three.
She could hum a Bach concerto.
She was that kind of child.
She could explain the earth's movement but not tie her shoes.
This was Madeline's problem.
Children gifted in music are often celebrated, but early readers are not.
Everyone learns to read.
So being first isn't special - it's just annoying.
Madeline knew this.
Every morning, she took the notes from her lunch and put them in a shoebox in her closet.
At school, she pretended she didn't know how to read.
To Madeline, fitting in with other kids was so important.
Her mother never fit in.
Look what happened to her.
Elizabeth and Madeline live in the Southern California town of Commons.
Madeline lay in bed, waiting for her mom's gentle kiss on her forehead.
Then, Madeline heard her mom's car drive away to the television studio.
At the studio, Elizabeth would put on an apron and walk out onto the set.
The show was called Supper at Six, and Elizabeth Zott was a star.
Elizabeth was a research chemist until she became a TV star.
Food theft led to her discovery as a TV star.
Most of Madeline's classmates ate peanut butter and jelly sandwiches for lunch.
Elizabeth packed Madeline a tasty lunch of lasagna, zucchini, chopped kiwi, cherry tomatoes, and a salt shaker.
Everyone wanted Madeline's lunch.
Madeline gave her lunch away every day to a girl named Amanda Pine.
Madeline chose Amanda because she was the only one in the school who didn't make fun of her.
Elizabeth noticed Madeline losing weight.
As a scientist, Elizabeth wanted an explanation.
She calculated what her daughter needed to be healthy.
Weight loss was not possible.
Elizabeth met Amanda Pine and saw the tomato sauce on her lips.
Elizabeth then figured out who ate Madeline's food.
Elizabeth called for Mr. Pine as she walked into the local TV studio.
I've been calling you for three days, she said.
She then continued explaining his daughter was eating Madeleine's food.
Walter Pine was confused.
He stood and took in the glowing woman wearing a white lab coat in front of him.
Elizabeth was tall and stiff with beautiful blonde hair tied up using a pencil.
She stood with her hands on her hips.
As a long-time TV producer, Walter knew drama.
But this?
She was stunning.
He was literally stunned by her.
Was she auditioning for something?
Elizabeth explained why she was there.
Walter finally understood who she was.
Walter said that he and Mrs. Pine are divorced.
Elizabeth explained that she had no time to make Walter's daughter's lunch.
Then Elizabeth said, Does anyone have the time to teach the entire country to make food that matters?
I wish I did, but I don't.
Do you?
Elizabeth wasn't sure about the idea.
She was a research chemist.
She took the job because it paid more, and she had a child to support.
Supper at Six aired on TV four weeks later.
From the first day on set, Elizabeth had the it factor.
People didn't know what to make of her.
Elizabeth Zott was serious.
She never made jokes.
Her dishes were as honest and down-to-earth as she was.
By 6 months, Elizabeth was a rising star.
Her recipes were nutritious and hearty.
She made stews and casseroles all in under an hour.
People would say that when Elizabeth Zott finished cooking, an entire nation sat down to eat.
She ended every show with the line: Children, set the table.
Your mother needs a moment to herself.
A reporter called Elizabeth Luscious Lizzie.
The nickname quickly stuck.
Strangers called Elizabeth Luscious.
Madeline knew this nickname belittled her mother.
Elizabeth would lay in bed at night and wonder how her life came to this.
She already knew.
His name was Calvin Evans.
